WEBVTT

00:02.141 --> 00:04.210
(grand orchestral fanfare
playing)

00:25.464 --> 00:27.497
♪ ♪

00:47.486 --> 00:49.519
♪ ♪

01:05.999 --> 01:07.966
♪ ♪

01:08.001 --> 01:10.034
<i> (thunder rumbling softly)</i>

01:28.153 --> 01:29.823
<i> (thunder rumbling)</i>

01:42.541 --> 01:44.508
(wind howling)

01:44.543 --> 01:46.576
♪ ♪

02:05.366 --> 02:09.401
Constable, a boat's blown in
with the storm.

02:09.436 --> 02:11.502
(thunder crashing)

02:21.679 --> 02:23.217
God.

02:23.252 --> 02:24.911
Come on!

02:32.019 --> 02:34.052
(indistinct chatter)

02:35.396 --> 02:37.429
-Fletcher?
-(breathes heavily)

02:39.763 --> 02:43.831
I went aboard, sir,
to see if anyone was alive.

02:43.866 --> 02:45.602
And?

02:49.971 --> 02:51.443
What's that?

02:51.478 --> 02:53.214
Captain's log.

02:55.383 --> 02:58.252
ELIOT:
<i> This log is a record</i>

02:58.287 --> 02:59.748
<i> and a warning.</i>

02:59.783 --> 03:03.587
<i> And if it finds you,</i>
<i> God help you,</i>

03:03.622 --> 03:07.085
<i> as he has abandoned</i>
<i> the</i> Demeter.

03:08.088 --> 03:10.022
<i> We tried to stop him.</i>

03:10.057 --> 03:12.728
<i> If we didn't succeed,</i>

03:12.763 --> 03:15.302
<i> God have mercy on your souls.</i>

03:20.408 --> 03:22.474
I can't go back, sir.

03:23.444 --> 03:25.246
Come on.

03:28.240 --> 03:30.284
(thunder rumbling)

03:38.822 --> 03:40.855
(sails rustling)

03:47.633 --> 03:49.303
♪ ♪

04:09.490 --> 04:11.523
-(hooves clopping)
-(wheels creaking)

04:17.894 --> 04:19.630
(horse sputters)

04:25.836 --> 04:28.573
♪ ♪

04:45.757 --> 04:47.823
-(kids laughing)
-(lively chatter)

05:00.706 --> 05:02.541
(excited shouting)

05:07.548 --> 05:08.811
MAN:
Hey!

05:08.846 --> 05:10.879
-(laughter)
-(coins clinking)

05:12.080 --> 05:14.014
(sniffs)

05:14.951 --> 05:17.017
♪ ♪

05:26.193 --> 05:28.325
MAN: Hey, mister! Sit down!
It's your turn.

05:28.360 --> 05:30.096
MAN 2:
Come on, wake up.

05:30.131 --> 05:31.669
MAN 3:
Let's go back home.

05:31.704 --> 05:33.231
(chuckling)

05:34.234 --> 05:36.410
(lively chatter continues)

05:36.445 --> 05:37.939
MAN:
Oppa!

05:37.974 --> 05:39.974
(wheels creak)

05:40.977 --> 05:43.208
(speaks Romani)

05:44.244 --> 05:45.518
ELIOT:
<i> Sixth of July,</i>

05:45.553 --> 05:48.422
<i> made port in Varna, Bulgaria.</i>

05:48.457 --> 05:50.853
Don't wander far, Toby.
We're not staying long.

05:50.888 --> 05:53.625
TOBY:
I won't, Grandpa. I promise.

05:54.595 --> 05:57.255
ELIOT:
<i> Our crew was a few hands short.</i>

05:57.290 --> 05:58.729
WOJCHEK:
Captain.

05:58.764 --> 06:00.764
ELIOT:
<i> And I have tasked Mr. Wojchek</i>

06:00.799 --> 06:03.965
<i> to remedy this</i>
<i> before we take on cargo.</i>

06:04.000 --> 06:06.902
-(lively chatter, laughter)
-(coins clinking)

06:06.937 --> 06:10.411
The<i> Demeter</i> is looking for
hands all the way to England.

06:11.403 --> 06:12.479
I fold.

06:13.647 --> 06:16.274
Open your ears, men.

06:16.309 --> 06:19.783
<i> Demeter</i> needs
three able-bodied seamen.

06:19.818 --> 06:22.214
Bound for London.
We pay in gold.

06:22.249 --> 06:23.886
I'm able.

06:23.921 --> 06:25.954
And strong as an ox.

06:25.989 --> 06:28.022
(laughter)

06:33.964 --> 06:35.568
Who are you, boy?

06:35.603 --> 06:37.768
Clemens.

06:37.803 --> 06:40.771
You dress like an educated man.
Where did you go to school?

06:40.806 --> 06:42.872
University of Cambridge.

06:44.139 --> 06:47.074
I have a steady hand
with a needle, and, uh...

06:47.109 --> 06:49.516
I have supplies if you're
in need of a ship doctor.

06:49.551 --> 06:51.111
I-It's been a while,

06:51.146 --> 06:53.443
but I-I do know
my way around a boat, if not.

06:53.478 --> 06:55.984
Learning about boats ain't
the same as keeping one afloat.

06:56.019 --> 06:59.086
What did the sailor
ever learn from a book

06:59.121 --> 07:01.451
that did him an ounce of good
when he was lost at sea?

07:01.486 --> 07:03.827
Astronomy, for one.

07:05.061 --> 07:07.963
Can lose a chart.
You can lose a compass.

07:07.998 --> 07:10.163
But you can't lose
the stars, can you?

07:10.198 --> 07:13.507
Never met an Englishman in such
a hurry to return to England.

07:13.542 --> 07:15.300
Be gone as soon as we reach it,
no doubt.

07:17.139 --> 07:20.580
We need strong crew,
not passengers.

07:21.209 --> 07:22.549
Me?

07:22.584 --> 07:23.946
(men groaning, murmuring)

07:23.981 --> 07:25.046
You.

07:25.081 --> 07:27.015
No, never mind you.

07:43.396 --> 07:45.363
(conversation continues
in Romani)

07:49.611 --> 07:50.874
WOJCHEK:
What's he saying?

07:51.877 --> 07:53.679
He says they cannot stay.

07:53.714 --> 07:55.208
The hell they can't.

07:55.243 --> 07:56.913
We need their hands
or we lose the tide.

07:56.948 --> 07:59.014
He says they need to leave
before the sun sinks.

08:00.017 --> 08:01.885
What kind of nonsense is that?

08:08.597 --> 08:10.355
-(coins clink)
-MAN: For your men.

08:11.864 --> 08:13.226
We go now.

08:24.910 --> 08:26.239
Men!

08:30.278 --> 08:33.543
This is more than I paid
to bring the damn cargo here.

08:33.578 --> 08:35.446
What did he spit at the end?

08:35.481 --> 08:37.019
"Good leave"
or "good riddance"?

08:37.054 --> 08:39.417
"Good luck."

08:39.452 --> 08:41.485
♪ ♪

08:47.130 --> 08:49.636
-Come on, pull!
-(men grunting)

08:49.671 --> 08:51.638
Pull!

08:51.673 --> 08:52.771
Come on, pull!

08:54.566 --> 08:56.709
Pull!

08:56.744 --> 08:58.337
Come on, pull!

08:59.846 --> 09:01.307
Pull!

09:01.342 --> 09:03.078
-(chatter continues)
-(mechanical creaking)

09:13.761 --> 09:16.124
MAN:
See, let go. Let go!

09:22.330 --> 09:24.363
♪ ♪

09:28.776 --> 09:30.809
-(lively chatter)
-(string music playing nearby)

09:38.786 --> 09:40.654
(grunting)

09:45.694 --> 09:47.221
(grunts)

09:56.969 --> 09:58.001
-(woman screams)
-(people murmuring)

09:58.036 --> 09:59.431
Toby!

09:59.466 --> 10:02.302
-Are you all right, boy?
-(coughing)

10:02.337 --> 10:03.842
ELIOT:
Toby?

10:05.241 --> 10:07.307
Mr. Wojchek, hold that man!

10:07.342 --> 10:10.046
You never said
nothing about dragons.

10:11.049 --> 10:12.983
I know this mark.

10:13.018 --> 10:15.018
It is a bad omen.

10:15.053 --> 10:16.690
WOJCHEK:
You could have killed the boy.

10:16.725 --> 10:18.516
I don't give a whore's ass
about dragons!

10:18.551 --> 10:22.729
Keep your gold,
the devil's serpent.

10:22.764 --> 10:24.159
God save you all.

10:24.194 --> 10:26.491
May he save the ship.

10:26.526 --> 10:28.526
May he save the crew.

10:31.498 --> 10:32.662
Are you all right?

10:32.697 --> 10:34.070
-You injured?
-Mm-mm.

10:38.109 --> 10:40.571
-Thank you, Mr. Clemens.
-Yeah, sure.

10:51.760 --> 10:53.584
We leave port within the hour.

10:53.619 --> 10:55.729
You prove to be lying about
knowing your way around a boat,

10:55.764 --> 10:58.523
I'll throw you off the boat
myself, astronomer.

10:59.526 --> 11:01.196
Uh, th-thank you, sir.

11:01.231 --> 11:03.869
Larsen, get this stinking bunch
of cockroaches underway.

11:03.904 --> 11:05.695
LARSEN:
You heard Mr. Wojchek.

11:05.730 --> 11:08.368
Olgaren,
get those crates stowed.

11:08.403 --> 11:10.436
♪ ♪

11:23.825 --> 11:25.451
TOBY:
Come on.

11:25.486 --> 11:27.761
-Good boy!
-(dog barking)

11:37.663 --> 11:39.564
Cast off! Ready the headsails.

11:40.842 --> 11:42.875
PETROFSKY:
Pull in the moorings!

11:42.910 --> 11:43.975
Be quick about it!

11:46.639 --> 11:48.441
(clanking)

11:50.016 --> 11:52.247
Pull!

11:52.282 --> 11:53.952
-Pull! -WOJCHEK: Give me
a way to steer.

11:53.987 --> 11:56.647
She moves like a fat pig
with all this weight.

11:56.682 --> 11:58.759
♪ ♪

12:18.209 --> 12:20.275
♪ ♪

12:39.065 --> 12:41.098
Do you see that beam up there?

12:41.133 --> 12:43.496
That's where they used to hang
pirates and mutineers.

12:43.531 --> 12:45.333
Have you ever seen
a real dead man, Mr. Clemens?

12:45.368 --> 12:46.840
I have.

12:46.875 --> 12:48.699
-Really?
-Let me show you the ship.

12:50.373 --> 12:53.176
Captain's cabin's
that big door.

12:53.211 --> 12:54.848
There's lots of maps
and drawings in there,

12:54.883 --> 12:57.477
but captain
doesn't like me fiddling.

12:57.512 --> 13:00.117
This here is Huckleberry.

13:00.152 --> 13:01.888
-Oh.
-But we just call him Huck.

13:01.923 --> 13:03.890
-(Huck barks)
-CLEMENS: Hello, Huck.

13:05.520 --> 13:06.893
That's the cargo hold.

13:06.928 --> 13:09.896
Everything there is
headed for London.

13:09.931 --> 13:12.327
You knock on wood like this
if there's any trouble.

13:12.362 --> 13:15.825
Or to signal a change of watch
or if the sky's looking fierce.

13:15.860 --> 13:17.827
You can hear it
all the way from the bunks

13:17.862 --> 13:19.829
to the captain's
on a clear night.

13:19.864 --> 13:21.402
-I swear.
-Mm.

13:21.437 --> 13:22.535
I've heard it.

13:22.570 --> 13:24.471
(laughs)
Yes, I believe you have.

13:24.506 --> 13:26.077
This is where we eat.

13:26.112 --> 13:28.013
This used to be a lumber ship,
built the old way.

13:28.048 --> 13:29.916
But now everyone wants
steam ships.

13:29.951 --> 13:32.314
Captain says there's no joy
in metal ships.

13:32.349 --> 13:33.986
Well, that's the thing
about progress, innit?

13:34.021 --> 13:37.891
It cares not for joy,
your captain's or otherwise.

13:37.926 --> 13:40.652
The<i> Demeter's</i> a fine boat.
No doubt.

13:40.687 --> 13:42.654
Meet my crew, Mr. Clemens.

13:42.689 --> 13:43.820
(animals bleating, squealing)

13:43.855 --> 13:45.492
The faster we eat them,

13:45.527 --> 13:47.164
the less crap
I have to clean up.

13:47.199 --> 13:48.902
-CLEMENS: Mm.
-(Huck barking, growling)

13:48.937 --> 13:51.036
TOBY: Ah-ah, Huck.
You know the rules.

13:51.071 --> 13:53.830
And up here is the galley.

13:53.865 --> 13:55.700
-Joseph.
-Huh?

13:55.735 --> 13:57.339
This here is Clemens.

13:57.374 --> 13:59.539
He's a doctor. A real one.

13:59.574 --> 14:02.916
JOSEPH: We eat at six bells--
no sooner, no later.

14:02.951 --> 14:04.775
You stay out of the galley.

14:04.810 --> 14:07.217
And I won't serve any man who
takes the Lord's name in vain.

14:07.252 --> 14:09.120
-He means that last one.
-I mean all of them.

14:09.155 --> 14:12.057
Do you know
who Saint Nicholas is?

14:12.092 --> 14:13.784
Patron saint of sailors.

14:15.392 --> 14:18.195
Well, you're not a heathen.

14:18.230 --> 14:20.131
Thank the Lord
for small favors.

14:20.166 --> 14:21.396
(laughs)

14:21.431 --> 14:23.431
Toby, show him to his quarters.

14:23.466 --> 14:25.400
And get this mutt
out of my kitchen.

14:25.435 --> 14:26.764
-TOBY: Huck!
-(panting)

14:26.799 --> 14:28.271
ELIOT:
<i> On sixth July,</i>

14:28.306 --> 14:30.405
<i> we finished taking in cargo--</i>

14:30.440 --> 14:33.045
<i> Turkish cotton,</i>
<i> ten barrels of petroleum</i>

14:33.080 --> 14:35.773
<i> and private crates</i>
<i> marked for London--</i>

14:35.808 --> 14:37.247
<i> with nine hands.</i>

14:37.282 --> 14:39.645
<i> Crew of five, one ship doctor,</i>

14:39.680 --> 14:42.714
<i> two mates, cook</i>
<i> and myself, captain.</i>

14:42.749 --> 14:44.452
<i> -Fair wind.</i>
-(upbeat music playing)

14:44.487 --> 14:46.322
<i> -Crew in high spirits.</i>
-(Toby laughing)

14:46.357 --> 14:48.456
♪ ♪

14:59.766 --> 15:03.240
PETROFSKY: ♪ Oh, they call me
Hangin' Johnny... ♪

15:03.275 --> 15:04.670
All is well, Captain.

15:04.705 --> 15:07.112
Making about 12 knots
on the nor'easter.

15:07.147 --> 15:10.082
Wheel's kicking a bit,
but she'll settle down.

15:10.117 --> 15:11.941
12 knots?

15:11.976 --> 15:15.318
We'll reach London
well before August the sixth.

15:15.353 --> 15:16.517
Aye, sir.

15:16.552 --> 15:18.618
For the crew's sake, we better.

15:18.653 --> 15:21.423
Already finding ways
to spend the bonus pay.

15:21.458 --> 15:23.359
♪ The holy family ♪

15:23.394 --> 15:26.263
♪ So hang, boys, hang ♪

15:26.298 --> 15:30.003
♪ They say
I hung my mother... ♪

15:30.038 --> 15:34.700
I've decided this is to be
my final voyage, Mr. Wojchek.

15:35.901 --> 15:38.308
I'm going to buy
a little cottage in Ireland.

15:38.343 --> 15:40.508
Toby will enjoy
the countryside.

15:40.543 --> 15:43.841
And I promised my daughter
I wouldn't let the sea air

15:43.876 --> 15:45.546
bleach the future out of him.

15:45.581 --> 15:47.647
I intend to keep that promise.

15:47.682 --> 15:49.649
I will arrange for you
to be my successor

15:49.684 --> 15:52.355
as captain of the<i> Demeter</i>
as soon as we reach London.

15:52.390 --> 15:53.851
Sir, I...

15:53.886 --> 15:55.820
You're a good seaman,
Mr. Wojchek.

15:55.855 --> 15:59.164
The ship couldn't ask for a
better hand to guide her crew.

15:59.199 --> 16:01.859
(singing continues in distance)

16:01.894 --> 16:04.532
♪ Away, boys, away ♪

16:04.567 --> 16:08.503
♪ They call me Hangin' Johnny ♪

16:08.538 --> 16:15.345
♪ So hang, boys, hang. ♪

16:15.380 --> 16:17.347
(laughter, whooping
in distance)

16:17.382 --> 16:19.415
♪ ♪

16:40.405 --> 16:43.208
(rat squeaking)

16:45.971 --> 16:48.048
(ship creaking softly)

16:50.712 --> 16:52.580
(squeaking)

16:55.717 --> 16:58.586
(soft hissing)

16:58.621 --> 17:00.192
(rats squeaking frantically)

17:00.227 --> 17:03.063
(low growling)

17:06.233 --> 17:08.200
(wood creaks)

17:08.235 --> 17:10.268
(growling)

17:13.768 --> 17:15.636
800 pounds eight ways,

17:15.671 --> 17:18.144
and minus the captain
and first mate's share,

17:18.179 --> 17:21.378
comes to round about...

17:21.413 --> 17:22.577
75 each.

17:22.612 --> 17:25.217
-75?
-Gonna get myself

17:25.252 --> 17:28.748
a proper shave and one of them
waistcoats with the tails on.

17:28.783 --> 17:31.080
Ooh, the English ladies
love them tails.

17:31.115 --> 17:33.951
Almost... almost as much
as they love me.

17:33.986 --> 17:36.162
If you put them
over your face, mm, maybe.

17:36.197 --> 17:37.592
-(laughter)
-Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah.

17:37.627 --> 17:39.022
You're the funny ones,
aren't you?

17:40.498 --> 17:41.992
What are you lot
gonna do with yours?

17:42.027 --> 17:43.994
JOSEPH: "The generous soul
will be made rich,

17:44.029 --> 17:47.371
and he who waters
will also be watered himself."

17:48.803 --> 17:50.308
Although the Lord
might not mind

17:50.343 --> 17:52.904
if I just simply
watered myself.

17:52.939 --> 17:54.147
(laughter)

17:54.182 --> 17:56.182
Oi! 75!

17:56.217 --> 17:57.942
Do you know
what I will do this much?

17:57.977 --> 18:00.318
(laughs) The same thing
that you always do, Petrofsky.

18:00.353 --> 18:02.320
Find the nearest brothel
and spend the next month

18:02.355 --> 18:04.520
absolutely up to
your gills in...

18:04.555 --> 18:06.291
Mr. Abrams, if you please.

18:06.326 --> 18:07.952
Apologies, Captain.

18:07.987 --> 18:10.163
-Forgot about the lad.
-TOBY: I'm almost nine.

18:10.198 --> 18:11.824
I know
what a brothel is, anyway.

18:11.859 --> 18:13.122
Do you, now?

18:13.157 --> 18:14.860
Yeah.

18:14.895 --> 18:16.862
It's a place we pay women
to take off their knickers.

18:16.897 --> 18:18.204
(laughter)

18:18.239 --> 18:20.129
-Ah, I love kids!
-(playful chatter)

18:20.164 --> 18:21.834
PETROFSKY:
Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah.

18:21.869 --> 18:23.033
TOBY:
Well, isn't it?

18:23.068 --> 18:24.375
ELIOT:
Oh, close enough, lad.

18:24.410 --> 18:26.344
Close enough.

18:26.379 --> 18:28.841
Well, Mr. Clemens,
what about you?

18:28.876 --> 18:30.975
-Sir?
-Our charter has agreed

18:31.010 --> 18:32.647
to pay a sizable bonus

18:32.682 --> 18:35.287
for timely arrival
of his cargo in London.

18:35.322 --> 18:36.783
You're part of the crew,

18:36.818 --> 18:39.291
which means you earn
a crewman's share.

18:39.326 --> 18:40.688
How do you plan spending it?

18:40.723 --> 18:44.791
A new petticoat, perhaps?

18:44.826 --> 18:46.562
Well, everything I desire
in this life, unfortunately,

18:46.597 --> 18:48.333
coin will be of no aid.

18:48.368 --> 18:51.127
(scoffs)
And what would that be, now?

18:51.162 --> 18:53.371
To understand this world.

18:53.406 --> 18:57.133
The more of it I see,
the less any of it makes sense.

18:57.168 --> 19:00.642
The world cares little
for sense, Mr. Clemens.

19:00.677 --> 19:03.810
Perhaps it is not meant
to be understood

19:03.845 --> 19:06.747
but rather experienced
and accepted.

19:10.423 --> 19:12.016
Perhaps.

19:13.855 --> 19:15.822
But I need to get
to the heart of it.

19:15.857 --> 19:18.330
And understand why

19:18.365 --> 19:23.269
the world has so much goodness
inside it and yet...

19:27.099 --> 19:29.902
(chuckles) Isn't that
what all men desire, mm?

19:31.576 --> 19:33.411
Deep down.

19:35.382 --> 19:37.349
ABRAMS:
Well, hell, he's right.

19:37.384 --> 19:39.417
I'll have his share, then.

19:39.452 --> 19:41.518
(laughter)

19:41.553 --> 19:43.080
-(animals squealing)
-(whining, barking)

19:43.115 --> 19:44.422
What the devil is that?

19:44.457 --> 19:47.458
ELIOT:
Toby. See to the livestock.

19:47.493 --> 19:50.395
(ship creaking)

19:50.430 --> 19:52.463
-(animals squealing wildly)
-Toby?

19:55.468 --> 19:57.501
(frantic thumping)

19:59.505 --> 20:01.230
What's gotten into them?

20:01.265 --> 20:03.804
It's probably just the weather.

20:03.839 --> 20:05.641
Hey, they can sense
a storm coming.

20:05.676 --> 20:08.512
(animals squealing frantically)

20:09.515 --> 20:11.207
(bleating)

20:11.242 --> 20:12.813
(squealing)

20:12.848 --> 20:14.584
(frantic clucking)

20:15.785 --> 20:18.258
Toby, give me a hand with this.

20:19.250 --> 20:21.591
That should put them to rest.

20:21.626 --> 20:23.593
(animals quiet down)

20:23.628 --> 20:25.958
(ship creaking, rattling)

20:29.095 --> 20:32.063
(objects clattering)

20:32.098 --> 20:34.439
What was that, Mr. Clemens?

20:34.474 --> 20:36.166
Fetch the captain, lad.

20:36.201 --> 20:38.311
Tell him something fell
in the cargo hold.

20:43.813 --> 20:45.846
-(grunts)
-(doors creaking)

21:00.225 --> 21:02.302
(ship creaking softly)

21:15.845 --> 21:17.845
(soft clanging in distance)

21:24.689 --> 21:26.722
♪ ♪

21:38.406 --> 21:40.032
(grunts softly)

21:48.878 --> 21:50.240
(grunts)

22:18.809 --> 22:20.875
(soft clanking in distance)

22:23.484 --> 22:24.912
(screams)

22:25.915 --> 22:27.948
(shallow gasping)

22:30.315 --> 22:33.250
(breathing heavily)

22:36.893 --> 22:38.563
-Stay with me.
-(woman whimpering softly)

22:40.094 --> 22:41.962
Stay with me.

22:41.997 --> 22:44.470
(grunts) Come on.

22:46.331 --> 22:49.167
-What in the seven hells?
-She was below deck.

22:50.137 --> 22:51.642
(woman whimpers)

22:51.677 --> 22:52.808
A stowaway.

22:52.843 --> 22:55.547
A stowaway who is going to die

22:55.582 --> 22:57.274
if we don't administer
proper medical care.

23:02.017 --> 23:04.083
You want to help her?

23:04.118 --> 23:08.384
Who knows what kind of diseased
rat infections she has...

23:08.419 --> 23:09.990
-Captain.
-What do you need?

23:10.025 --> 23:11.497
Her body's infected.

23:11.532 --> 23:13.092
I need to attempt
a transfusion.

23:13.127 --> 23:15.094
-What are you babbling?
-A blood transfusion.

23:15.129 --> 23:17.998
She needs blood
to fight the infection.

23:18.033 --> 23:19.901
WOJCHEK:
You're joking.

23:19.936 --> 23:22.739
You are of aid to me or you are
in my way and need to leave.

23:22.774 --> 23:24.675
In either case,
please make yourself apparent

23:24.710 --> 23:26.336
and fulfill your purpose.

23:26.371 --> 23:28.448
♪ ♪

23:54.069 --> 23:56.135
(whimpers weakly)

23:58.678 --> 24:00.711
(weak, muffled grunting)

24:04.585 --> 24:08.048
(shuddering breaths)

24:08.083 --> 24:10.017
-(wood creaking)
-(grunting)

24:13.660 --> 24:15.693
♪ ♪

24:19.523 --> 24:22.293
(exhale echoes)

24:22.328 --> 24:25.197
CLEMENS: She'll make it the
night, but I need to continue

24:25.232 --> 24:29.003
with the transfusions until
she has no more infected blood.

24:30.369 --> 24:32.644
We've done all we can.

24:32.679 --> 24:34.712
WOJCHEK: Then maybe she'll
wake up in time to see us

24:34.747 --> 24:37.143
toss her to the waves.

24:37.178 --> 24:40.982
We let Poseidon deal
with stowaways-- always have.

24:41.017 --> 24:44.480
I didn't save this girl's life
only to watch you end it.

24:44.515 --> 24:46.416
At least let us off
at the next port.

24:46.451 --> 24:48.055
"Us," is it?

24:48.090 --> 24:51.729
I see where your loyalty lies,
Mr. Clemens.

24:51.764 --> 24:54.831
We stop, then we forfeit
the bonus wage.

24:54.866 --> 24:57.262
And I ain't
forfeiting the bonus wage

24:57.297 --> 24:59.330
for you or your diseased whore.

24:59.365 --> 25:00.903
ELIOT:
Mr. Wojchek, lower your voice.

25:00.938 --> 25:02.432
Control your language.

25:02.467 --> 25:04.709
I would prefer not to have
my final voyage

25:04.744 --> 25:06.205
at the helm of the<i> Demeter</i>

25:06.240 --> 25:08.075
marred by the death
of a young woman.

25:08.110 --> 25:10.583
Stowaway or not.

25:14.215 --> 25:16.215
We will repurpose
the carpenter shed

25:16.250 --> 25:18.514
-as the young woman's quarters.
-Thank you, sir.

25:18.549 --> 25:21.924
And you will be solely dividing
your own rations

25:21.959 --> 25:23.959
with your patient, Mr. Clemens.

25:27.228 --> 25:29.261
♪ ♪

25:44.916 --> 25:46.443
CLEMENS:
Toby.

25:49.789 --> 25:52.548
-You'll look after her for me,
will you? -Mm-hmm.

25:52.583 --> 25:54.253
Anyone tries to see her,
you come get me

25:54.288 --> 25:57.091
-or the captain straightaway,
you understand? -Yeah.

25:57.126 --> 26:00.259
All right, then. Go on.
That's a good lad.

26:15.881 --> 26:17.474
OLGAREN: You're making
all sorts of friends,

26:17.509 --> 26:18.948
aren't you, Mr. Clemens?

26:20.281 --> 26:22.952
Woman on the ship.
Bad omen. Hmm?

26:22.987 --> 26:24.514
Bad luck.

26:24.549 --> 26:26.285
Men won't be happy.

26:26.320 --> 26:29.090
The men don't need to be happy,
do they, Mr. Olgaren?

26:29.125 --> 26:31.455
They just need to get this boat
to London, huh?

26:31.490 --> 26:33.490
(Olgaren chuckles)

26:33.525 --> 26:36.526
I'm trying to help you, son.
Keep spouting words like that.

26:36.561 --> 26:38.198
Maybe she'll make it
to London, but...

26:38.233 --> 26:39.837
but I reckon
you'll be swimming.

26:39.872 --> 26:41.168
(chuckles)

26:41.203 --> 26:43.676
Knock if you need me.

26:43.711 --> 26:45.678
-Saves the pipes.
-Mm.

26:45.713 --> 26:47.911
-Understand?
-Aye!

26:58.385 --> 27:00.990
Islands and rocks
everywhere here.

27:01.025 --> 27:03.289
So we're in the Aegean, yes?

27:03.324 --> 27:05.489
It's the Mediterranean at dawn.

27:06.525 --> 27:07.931
It's good time, innit?

27:09.660 --> 27:12.232
Greece should be
to our starboard.

27:13.840 --> 27:16.335
(hissing, growling)

27:18.405 --> 27:20.438
♪ ♪

27:45.234 --> 27:47.267
♪ ♪

27:56.817 --> 27:58.080
Mr. Olgaren?

28:17.431 --> 28:18.628
Mr. Olgaren?

28:18.663 --> 28:20.740
♪ ♪

28:35.581 --> 28:38.615
(knocks echoing)

28:43.754 --> 28:44.797
(distant knock)

28:51.201 --> 28:52.871
Olgaren?

28:54.006 --> 28:56.303
♪ ♪

29:05.281 --> 29:08.854
(screams) Jesus Christ!

29:08.889 --> 29:10.647
Did you see it?

29:10.682 --> 29:12.187
Did no one pass by?

29:12.222 --> 29:14.893
See what?
There's no one on deck but us.

29:15.896 --> 29:18.490
There is something out there.

29:22.034 --> 29:23.363
Someone.

29:33.507 --> 29:35.540
♪ ♪

29:39.744 --> 29:41.821
(panting)

29:49.589 --> 29:52.359
(soft hissing)

29:55.661 --> 29:57.694
♪ ♪

30:05.836 --> 30:07.880
(barking)

30:15.450 --> 30:17.890
(whimpering)

30:17.925 --> 30:20.552
-(sharp whoosh)
-(growl echoes)

30:26.461 --> 30:27.933
(sighs)

30:34.942 --> 30:36.535
(grunts) What the...

30:42.873 --> 30:45.214
(gasps) Oh, God, Huck.

30:47.713 --> 30:50.615
♪ ♪

30:50.650 --> 30:53.222
(flies buzzing)

31:11.473 --> 31:13.242
All the livestock?

31:17.644 --> 31:22.218
Any man with knowledge
of this heinous act

31:22.253 --> 31:26.222
needs to step forward now or
find themselves in irons later.

31:26.257 --> 31:28.224
(spits, smacks lips)

31:28.259 --> 31:29.753
The girl...

31:29.788 --> 31:31.623
Was in no shape
to do anything of the sort,

31:31.658 --> 31:34.428
and Mr. Wojchek can attest to
that, even if he'd rather not.

31:35.431 --> 31:36.969
Aye.

31:37.004 --> 31:38.971
He's right on this.

31:39.006 --> 31:41.468
PETROFSKY: She didn't need to.
We all know.

31:41.503 --> 31:44.834
Bad luck, woman on board.

31:44.869 --> 31:47.441
Makes skies turn,
animals go mad.

31:47.476 --> 31:48.981
The dog was ripped into.

31:49.016 --> 31:52.248
Perhaps he went rabid
and was gored by

31:52.283 --> 31:54.151
one of the larger livestock
as it attacked it.

31:54.186 --> 31:56.615
You think Huck did this?

31:56.650 --> 31:58.254
Ripped apart the animals?

31:58.289 --> 32:00.949
No. He's a good dog.

32:00.984 --> 32:02.522
WOJCHEK:
You heard the man.

32:02.557 --> 32:04.689
Rabies. Bad luck is all.

32:04.724 --> 32:07.098
Push on through as we always do.

32:07.133 --> 32:12.202
If this is an outbreak,
then we'll need to make port.

32:12.237 --> 32:14.501
-Captain... -No. No. -No,
we won't make our bonus, then.

32:14.536 --> 32:16.338
What are you talking about?
Then we lose the bonus wage.

32:16.373 --> 32:17.834
We can't make port. No.

32:17.869 --> 32:21.277
ELIOT: Mr. Clemens,
a malady of this sort,

32:21.312 --> 32:23.411
could a human catch it?

32:30.585 --> 32:32.882
No.

32:32.917 --> 32:36.688
Rabies, it-it can't pass to
a human without it being bit.

32:40.364 --> 32:42.331
Dispose of the meat.

32:43.334 --> 32:45.169
Immediately.

32:45.204 --> 32:47.171
JOSEPH: I guess we say
the Lord's Prayer

32:47.206 --> 32:49.635
over cabbage and potatoes
for the rest of our voyage.

32:49.670 --> 32:51.406
(clattering)

32:52.574 --> 32:55.003
Have you all been struck dumb?

32:55.038 --> 33:00.316
It's not rabies that opened up
the livestock cages.

33:00.351 --> 33:02.318
And there is only
two people on this boat

33:02.353 --> 33:04.320
I have not sailed with fore now:

33:04.355 --> 33:06.982
the<i> cyka</i> in the toolshed

33:07.017 --> 33:10.755
and this darky savage
pretending to be doctor.

33:10.790 --> 33:13.296
-Mm?
-(sighs)

33:14.530 --> 33:16.233
Say it again.

33:17.599 --> 33:18.862
(speaks Russian)

33:25.607 --> 33:26.936
OLGAREN:
No man did this.

33:30.711 --> 33:32.909
Evil is on board.

33:32.944 --> 33:34.317
Powerful evil.

33:36.288 --> 33:38.321
(shuddering breaths)

33:41.557 --> 33:43.920
(heart beating slowly)

33:43.955 --> 33:45.988
♪ ♪

33:51.831 --> 33:53.897
(heartbeat continues faster)

34:05.515 --> 34:08.813
DRACULA (growling):
Anna.

34:10.256 --> 34:12.685
-(water splashes)
-That bloody reeks.

34:15.624 --> 34:17.162
(grunts)

34:17.197 --> 34:19.263
(Toby crying softly)

34:23.533 --> 34:25.170
CLEMENS:
Toby?

34:28.604 --> 34:30.670
(sobbing)

34:35.347 --> 34:36.808
Toby?

34:38.713 --> 34:39.910
Hey.

34:39.945 --> 34:41.978
(crying softly)

34:43.223 --> 34:45.388
Huck was a good dog, son.

34:47.788 --> 34:48.952
I'm sorry.

34:48.987 --> 34:52.923
It wasn't just Huckleberry.

34:52.958 --> 34:54.826
I promised the captain I--

34:54.861 --> 34:58.203
It was my job
to look after them.

34:58.238 --> 34:59.963
The animals, I mean.

34:59.998 --> 35:02.834
I-I promised the captain.

35:05.212 --> 35:06.475
Hmm.

35:10.877 --> 35:12.976
Toby...

35:13.011 --> 35:17.046
sometimes things go wrong,
no matter what we promise.

35:18.918 --> 35:20.621
All right?

35:20.656 --> 35:24.460
There are things in this world
that we can't control,

35:24.495 --> 35:27.958
but we do our best. Hmm?

35:27.993 --> 35:29.465
Yeah.

35:29.500 --> 35:31.236
Thanks, Mr. Clemens.

35:33.702 --> 35:35.504
Go on.

35:42.612 --> 35:44.678
♪ ♪

35:51.423 --> 35:53.456
(Dracula growling)

35:58.265 --> 36:00.298
-(thunder crashing)
-(wind howling)

36:04.799 --> 36:06.865
(ship creaking)

36:11.740 --> 36:12.970
(Clemens grunts)

36:15.480 --> 36:16.908
(grunts)

36:17.911 --> 36:19.383
The skies are angry.

36:19.418 --> 36:21.176
CLEMENS: The skies
feel nothing, my friend.

36:21.211 --> 36:23.915
It's precipitation
and air pressure,

36:23.950 --> 36:26.258
as knowable as
the workings of this ship.

36:26.293 --> 36:29.019
I saw something last night.

36:29.054 --> 36:31.219
There is something unnatural
on board with us.

36:31.254 --> 36:33.925
I'm afraid I don't believe
in superstitions, Mr. Olgaren.

36:33.960 --> 36:37.929
I believe in science
and in nature.

36:37.964 --> 36:39.535
And in Saint Nicholas,

36:39.570 --> 36:40.767
since Joseph wouldn't
give me food otherwise.

36:40.802 --> 36:42.230
Keep your science.

36:42.265 --> 36:44.573
I saw your face
in the dark last night.

36:44.608 --> 36:46.608
Your eyes.

36:47.743 --> 36:51.316
You saw it, same as I.

36:52.275 --> 36:54.319
♪ ♪

37:00.085 --> 37:02.085
ELIOT:
<i> 16th of July.</i>

37:02.120 --> 37:06.463
<i> Rough weather last three days</i>
<i> and all hands busy with sails.</i>

37:07.664 --> 37:09.499
<i> Our ship's doctor continues</i>

37:09.534 --> 37:12.436
<i> to administer regular</i>
<i> transfusions to our stowaway,</i>

37:12.471 --> 37:16.132
<i> yet her condition</i>
<i> remains unchanged.</i>

37:16.167 --> 37:18.970
<i> Food is running sparse,</i>

37:19.005 --> 37:21.236
<i> men downcast,</i>

37:21.271 --> 37:23.744
<i> and now past Cape Matapan,</i>

37:23.779 --> 37:26.351
<i> we've more than two weeks</i>
<i> to travel.</i>

37:28.718 --> 37:29.948
(speaking Romani quietly)

37:29.983 --> 37:31.246
TOBY:
Her name is Anna.

37:31.281 --> 37:33.358
CLEMENS:
She told you that?

37:33.393 --> 37:34.854
Has she been awake?

37:34.889 --> 37:37.120
Mr. Olgaren taught me
some Romani.

37:37.155 --> 37:39.562
She speaks some English
sometimes, too.

37:43.029 --> 37:46.030
She didn't say this one
so much, but...

37:46.065 --> 37:48.406
I don't think
she's having very nice dreams.

37:49.706 --> 37:53.510
She repeats a word
over and over.

37:53.545 --> 37:54.874
(Toby speaks Romani)

37:54.909 --> 37:56.513
"Feed."

37:57.747 --> 37:59.648
(sighs)

37:59.683 --> 38:01.980
♪ ♪

38:02.015 --> 38:04.048
(wheel creaking)

38:10.056 --> 38:11.924
JOSEPH:
Can't sleep?

38:13.829 --> 38:15.697
You noticed it, too, then.

38:19.329 --> 38:22.231
The rats.

38:22.266 --> 38:23.903
Still quiet.

38:23.938 --> 38:25.971
I was checking the larder.
They're all gone.

38:26.006 --> 38:29.304
Gone? What do you mean gone?

38:29.339 --> 38:31.207
I mean what I say. Gone.

38:31.242 --> 38:34.419
Always a dozen or so
in the woodwork,

38:34.454 --> 38:37.213
screeching, scrabbling.

38:37.248 --> 38:39.149
Well, if... if Huck went rabid,

38:39.184 --> 38:41.492
perhaps, before the livestock,
he drove them off...

38:41.527 --> 38:45.430
You could burn this ship
to the keel, Mr. Clemens,

38:45.465 --> 38:48.763
and the rats would
just nest in the ashes.

38:51.636 --> 38:53.438
(knocks echoing)

38:53.473 --> 38:55.737
Something drove them off.

39:02.713 --> 39:05.417
A boat without rats,

39:05.452 --> 39:08.079
such a thing is against nature.

39:18.465 --> 39:20.498
(loud thump in distance)

39:30.477 --> 39:32.235
Abrams?

39:34.107 --> 39:37.339
Playing some kind
of fool's joke.

39:41.081 --> 39:43.345
Idiots playing games, huh?

39:45.316 --> 39:46.491
Abrams?

39:47.450 --> 39:49.252
(ship creaking)

40:17.117 --> 40:18.886
(mutters in Russian)

40:27.226 --> 40:29.292
(quiet groaning, retching)

40:36.301 --> 40:38.543
(quiet groaning continues)

40:49.853 --> 40:51.886
(quiet wheezing)

40:53.692 --> 40:55.725
(groaning)

41:03.064 --> 41:05.097
(groaning continues)

41:09.576 --> 41:13.006
Where the hell
did you come from?

41:13.041 --> 41:15.239
(snarling)

41:15.274 --> 41:17.978
(gasping)

41:18.013 --> 41:20.046
(choking)

41:26.890 --> 41:29.792
(gasping weakly)

41:33.600 --> 41:34.962
(grunts)

41:36.636 --> 41:37.932
(panting)

41:42.367 --> 41:44.609
(growling)

41:47.372 --> 41:49.306
-(roaring)
-(grunting)

41:53.620 --> 41:55.246
(neck snaps)

41:56.381 --> 41:58.414
(gulping)

42:04.587 --> 42:06.158
(whimpering weakly)

42:07.128 --> 42:09.161
(growling)

42:17.677 --> 42:20.304
♪ ♪

42:29.656 --> 42:31.315
(soft thump)

42:31.350 --> 42:33.152
Petrofsky?

42:48.939 --> 42:50.972
♪ ♪

43:01.853 --> 43:05.184
(bell clanging)

43:05.219 --> 43:07.285
-(chewing)
-(flesh ripping)

43:11.390 --> 43:14.523
ELIOT:
The knife was found here?

43:14.558 --> 43:16.492
And the wheel was tied off?

43:16.527 --> 43:18.626
Petrofsky must have been drunk.

43:18.661 --> 43:21.772
Slipped on the deck
and (scoffs) fell overboard.

43:21.807 --> 43:23.807
Right after he bled
all over the deck?

43:25.173 --> 43:27.943
And what were you doing up
in the middle of the night?

43:27.978 --> 43:30.440
You had his knife in your hand
when we found you.

43:30.475 --> 43:32.981
Of course. I-I killed him.

43:33.016 --> 43:34.642
And somehow managed
to keep myself

43:34.677 --> 43:36.644
free of all the blood
you see staining the boards,

43:36.679 --> 43:38.646
then I rang the signal bell
to report myself.

43:38.681 --> 43:40.186
It's quite brilliant,
innit, Mr. Wojchek?

43:40.221 --> 43:41.253
Open-and-shut case.

43:48.735 --> 43:50.768
(panting softly)

43:53.905 --> 43:57.170
Captain, the dog's body,
I examined it.

43:57.205 --> 44:00.569
It wasn't killed in the larder
like the other animals.

44:00.604 --> 44:04.177
It had bite marks on its neck.
All the animals did.

44:05.884 --> 44:07.851
ELIOT: What exactly are you
suggesting, Mr. Clemens?

44:07.886 --> 44:09.985
CLEMENS:
I don't know, sir,

44:10.020 --> 44:12.053
but their arteries were
ripped open, and then they...

44:12.088 --> 44:13.186
(whispers):
He's here.

44:15.421 --> 44:17.091
He is here.

44:17.126 --> 44:19.357
We have to get off this boat.
Now!

44:19.392 --> 44:21.491
All of us!
We have to get off this boat!

44:21.526 --> 44:23.328
-Mr. Clemens, restrain
your patient. -(Anna shouting)

44:23.363 --> 44:25.561
-Now! He will kill us all!
-Please! Anna, please!

44:25.596 --> 44:27.035
-Anna, please! Please!
-Kill us all!

44:27.070 --> 44:29.400
-Get off the boat. (sobbing)
-(shushing)

44:29.435 --> 44:30.940
(Toby panting)

44:30.975 --> 44:33.107
(Anna crying)

44:35.947 --> 44:38.376
Captain will say a few words
from the good book,

44:38.411 --> 44:40.378
and we'll get on with things.

44:40.413 --> 44:42.083
There's not enough liquor
on board to get Petrofsky

44:42.118 --> 44:43.887
-drunk enough to fall off...
-Mr. Abrams.

44:43.922 --> 44:45.416
Are we not gonna listen to
the lass and what she just...

44:45.451 --> 44:48.023
I'll spend no more time
discussing anything

44:48.058 --> 44:52.060
but the state of this boat
and the weather.

44:52.095 --> 44:55.129
Understood, Mr. Abrams?
Get to work.

44:58.002 --> 44:59.661
(sobbing)

45:01.071 --> 45:02.730
ELIOT:
<i> 18th of July.</i>

45:02.765 --> 45:04.402
<i> Men reported in the morning</i>

45:04.437 --> 45:07.273
<i> that one of the crew,</i>
<i> Petrofsky, was missing.</i>

45:07.308 --> 45:10.276
<i> I had the men do</i>
<i> a thorough search of the ship.</i>

45:10.311 --> 45:12.212
<i> This after Olgaren confided</i>

45:12.247 --> 45:15.952
<i> that he had seen something</i>
<i> strange nights before.</i>

45:17.318 --> 45:19.351
♪ ♪

45:25.194 --> 45:26.798
CLEMENS:
These blood transfusions

45:26.833 --> 45:29.493
should keep your infection
under control.

45:31.497 --> 45:36.137
So, what were you trying
to tell us out there?

45:39.142 --> 45:42.308
He is here on the ship.

45:42.343 --> 45:44.046
He has been all along.

45:45.544 --> 45:47.478
He?

45:49.988 --> 45:51.449
(Clemens scoffs)

45:53.057 --> 45:54.683
Okay.

45:54.718 --> 45:57.961
I can't help you
if you don't speak to me

45:57.996 --> 46:01.063
and tell me what happened,
why we found you below deck.

46:05.905 --> 46:10.336
It is spoken in my village
of an evil

46:10.371 --> 46:13.273
that lives
in the mountains above.

46:13.308 --> 46:17.805
A castle older than any of us.

46:17.840 --> 46:20.676
-Evil?
-An evil that appears as a man

46:20.711 --> 46:22.953
when it wants to hide
its true nature.

46:22.988 --> 46:26.550
And at night, he feeds
on the blood of the innocent.

46:26.585 --> 46:30.026
I have lived in the shadow
of that castle my whole life.

46:31.161 --> 46:34.492
I knew that the elders, they...

46:34.527 --> 46:39.200
they made bargains
for the safety of our people.

46:39.235 --> 46:40.971
You were given to this man?

46:41.006 --> 46:43.666
-It is not a man.
-Then an animal?

46:43.701 --> 46:46.471
No, it is not
some mindless animal either.

46:46.506 --> 46:47.945
Do not make that mistake.

46:49.509 --> 46:52.576
We call him Dracula.

46:52.611 --> 46:55.678
And you-you believe
that he brought you on board?

46:59.288 --> 47:00.584
Why?

47:01.554 --> 47:03.587
♪ ♪

47:12.202 --> 47:15.104
ANNA:
He brought me here to feed.

47:15.139 --> 47:16.732
Dear God.

47:19.902 --> 47:22.408
He is here, Mr. Clemens.

47:24.115 --> 47:28.381
<i> The thing that wears</i>
<i> the skin of a man.</i>

47:28.416 --> 47:30.614
<i> In the night,</i>
<i> it drinks our blood,</i>

47:30.649 --> 47:33.056
and he is on this ship.

47:33.091 --> 47:35.289
Which means
that we will never leave it.

47:36.919 --> 47:38.963
(thunder crashing)

47:46.665 --> 47:48.533
The woman,

47:48.568 --> 47:51.371
she seems harmless, but...

47:51.406 --> 47:54.572
ever since she came on board,
I wonder if...

47:54.607 --> 47:57.839
if we would have been better
just to let the ocean have her.

48:00.745 --> 48:02.679
But then I think about
my daughter.

48:05.453 --> 48:08.256
She's around her age and...

48:08.291 --> 48:10.588
smart and-and pretty.

48:10.623 --> 48:12.854
(thunder crashing)

48:20.105 --> 48:22.138
(ship creaking)

48:25.176 --> 48:26.637
-(soft whoosh)
-(exhale echoes)

48:26.672 --> 48:28.705
(quiet hissing)

48:52.863 --> 48:54.896
♪ ♪

49:16.887 --> 49:18.920
♪ ♪

49:22.233 --> 49:24.200
(thunder rumbling)

49:31.935 --> 49:34.012
(knocks echoing)

49:40.284 --> 49:41.778
Olgaren?

49:50.261 --> 49:51.920
Olgaren?

49:55.233 --> 49:57.266
(knocks echoing)

50:09.247 --> 50:13.084
What's wrong?
I heard your knock.

50:13.119 --> 50:14.943
My knock?

50:14.978 --> 50:16.945
(knocking)

50:21.556 --> 50:23.589
♪ ♪

50:40.509 --> 50:42.575
(thunder rumbling)

50:45.349 --> 50:46.645
(wood creaking)

50:49.254 --> 50:51.782
-(snarling)
-(Larsen grunts)

50:51.817 --> 50:53.784
(screaming)

50:53.819 --> 50:55.687
(grunting)

51:00.199 --> 51:01.462
(hissing)

51:01.497 --> 51:03.629
Please, no!

51:03.664 --> 51:05.994
(shouts)

51:13.476 --> 51:14.673
(roars)

51:14.708 --> 51:18.611
Please, no.

51:18.646 --> 51:20.646
(grunting)

51:23.651 --> 51:25.882
(ship creaking loudly)

51:27.853 --> 51:30.227
(objects clattering)

51:35.234 --> 51:36.662
(yells)

51:41.163 --> 51:43.669
(thunder crashing)

51:43.704 --> 51:44.769
(yells)

51:44.804 --> 51:46.606
(grunts, yells)

51:46.641 --> 51:47.970
WOJCHEK:
Pull, you bastards!

51:48.005 --> 51:49.279
Pull!

51:49.314 --> 51:51.248
-(grunts)
-(yells)

51:55.045 --> 51:57.518
(grunting)

52:01.183 --> 52:02.820
Abrams!

52:02.855 --> 52:05.086
Where the devil is Larsen?!

52:08.399 --> 52:11.125
-Larsen! Larsen!
-Larsen! Larsen!

52:11.160 --> 52:13.600
-Olgaren!
-Larsen!

52:18.101 --> 52:20.068
Larsen!

52:21.170 --> 52:23.709
-Larsen!
-Larsen!

52:23.744 --> 52:26.074
ABRAMS:
Larsen!

52:28.287 --> 52:30.353
♪ ♪

52:50.903 --> 52:52.936
♪ ♪

52:55.237 --> 52:57.644
(screaming)

53:00.649 --> 53:03.518
-That's it. (grunts)
-(men grunting)

53:03.553 --> 53:05.619
Olgaren, where's Larsen?

53:05.654 --> 53:08.556
Olgaren. Hey.

53:08.591 --> 53:09.854
CLEMENS:
There he is.

53:09.889 --> 53:11.757
-(grunting)
-(shouts) Hold him!

53:11.792 --> 53:12.758
Guys!

53:12.793 --> 53:16.300
(screaming)

53:16.335 --> 53:18.896
ELIOT:
<i> 24th of July.</i>

53:18.931 --> 53:22.603
<i> There seems some doom</i>
<i> over the ship,</i>

53:22.638 --> 53:25.705
<i> already a hand short</i>
<i> entering the Bay of Biscay</i>

53:25.740 --> 53:27.806
<i> with wild weather ahead.</i>

53:27.841 --> 53:33.482
<i> And last night, a second man</i>
<i> lost and another man injured.</i>

53:33.517 --> 53:36.144
<i> A strange injury.</i>

53:36.179 --> 53:39.422
<i> Men all in a panic of fear.</i>

53:41.019 --> 53:43.052
<i> We are 18 days at sea.</i>

53:43.087 --> 53:45.989
<i> The closest port is England.</i>

53:47.025 --> 53:50.994
<i> We must put our trust in God</i>
<i> and go forward.</i>

53:51.029 --> 53:52.765
(soft clatter)

53:52.800 --> 53:54.470
(sighs)

53:58.344 --> 53:59.970
CLEMENS:
<i> He's cold as ice.</i>

54:00.005 --> 54:03.611
He makes noises and he moves,
but his eyes won't open.

54:03.646 --> 54:06.108
Like he's unable to wake
from some dream.

54:06.143 --> 54:07.747
But what happened to his neck?

54:07.782 --> 54:09.144
And what was he doing
in the rigging?

54:09.179 --> 54:11.586
Anything could have happened.

54:11.621 --> 54:15.656
Perhaps some rigging
wrapped around his throat.

54:15.691 --> 54:17.284
No. No, no, no.

54:17.319 --> 54:19.088
This looks like a bite.

54:19.123 --> 54:21.662
It looks like the same bites
we saw in the animals,

54:21.697 --> 54:23.499
the same bites that ravaged the
girl in the carpenter's shed.

54:23.534 --> 54:25.963
WOJCHEK:
You think some devil did this?

54:25.998 --> 54:28.097
Like she says?

54:28.132 --> 54:29.802
I...

54:33.841 --> 54:35.643
...do not.

54:35.678 --> 54:37.975
-Good.
-But something did.

54:39.176 --> 54:41.517
And that is real and on board,

54:41.552 --> 54:44.179
whether we choose
to believe in it or not.

54:50.528 --> 54:52.660
From now on,

54:52.695 --> 54:56.796
I want two men
for every watch, armed.

54:56.831 --> 54:59.634
No exceptions.

54:59.669 --> 55:02.098
Search the ship, Mr. Wojchek.

55:03.673 --> 55:06.410
Not just the hold.

55:06.445 --> 55:07.675
Everywhere.

55:07.710 --> 55:09.743
♪ ♪

55:25.695 --> 55:27.728
(Clemens grunting)

55:30.095 --> 55:32.128
♪ ♪

55:54.955 --> 55:56.757
All right, Toby.

55:58.222 --> 56:00.794
You have quite the task.

56:05.229 --> 56:07.570
A captain... (sighs)

56:07.605 --> 56:09.803
is only as good as his spyglass.

56:11.235 --> 56:13.576
Can I trust you
to shine it up for me?

56:14.777 --> 56:16.579
If it's too much to...

56:16.614 --> 56:18.075
No.

56:19.683 --> 56:22.079
I mean, no, sir.

56:22.114 --> 56:24.851
I can do it, I swear.

56:25.854 --> 56:27.084
Good lad.

56:28.417 --> 56:30.461
-(door opens)
-I'll be back soon.

56:31.453 --> 56:34.289
Toby, lock the door.

56:39.032 --> 56:40.295
(grunts)

56:40.330 --> 56:42.671
(Abrams breathing heavily)

56:42.706 --> 56:44.673
ABRAMS:
I don't like this.

56:44.708 --> 56:47.511
Sun's going down,
and he'll be coming.

56:49.009 --> 56:51.042
♪ ♪

57:01.725 --> 57:03.791
(Olgaren grunting)

57:05.795 --> 57:08.697
♪ ♪

57:08.732 --> 57:11.425
(thumping)

57:11.460 --> 57:12.833
(rapid thumping)

57:15.541 --> 57:18.036
(rapid thumping continues)

57:19.842 --> 57:21.072
(screams)

57:23.076 --> 57:25.010
(breathes sharply)

57:30.754 --> 57:32.721
(low growling in distance)

57:32.756 --> 57:34.723
(breath shudders)

57:40.698 --> 57:42.698
(door creaks)

57:47.529 --> 57:49.001
Hello?

58:07.219 --> 58:09.692
(door creaking)

58:09.727 --> 58:11.089
(grunts)

58:15.557 --> 58:18.261
(door clanking)

58:18.296 --> 58:20.362
-(ragged breathing)
-(slow footsteps)

58:31.408 --> 58:33.782
Mr. Olgaren, you're up.

58:35.115 --> 58:37.951
(wheezing softly)

58:37.986 --> 58:39.920
Mister...?

58:39.955 --> 58:42.758
♪ ♪

58:57.269 --> 58:59.302
-(gasps)
-(shouts)

58:59.337 --> 59:00.611
(screams)

59:00.646 --> 59:02.305
(gasping)

59:05.244 --> 59:06.375
(Toby yells)

59:06.410 --> 59:08.344
-(grunting)
-(fabric rips)

59:11.613 --> 59:13.514
(panting)

59:16.662 --> 59:18.486
(grunting)

59:19.489 --> 59:21.522
(grunting)

59:31.369 --> 59:32.808
(grunting)

59:32.843 --> 59:34.843
(panting)

59:34.878 --> 59:36.944
(ragged breathing outside)

59:48.188 --> 59:49.693
Mr. Olgaren?

59:58.198 --> 01:00:01.936
Mr. Olgaren,
will you please go away?

01:00:01.971 --> 01:00:04.840
(ragged breathing)

01:00:24.763 --> 01:00:26.862
-(bang on door)
-(screams)

01:00:29.526 --> 01:00:30.833
(bang on door)

01:00:32.166 --> 01:00:34.364
(growls)

01:00:35.169 --> 01:00:37.169
-(shouts)
-(banging continues)

01:00:45.212 --> 01:00:47.542
(whimpers):
Please.

01:00:52.516 --> 01:00:54.648
That's every mast.

01:00:54.683 --> 01:00:57.618
Any other strokes of genius,
Mr. Clemens?

01:01:08.598 --> 01:01:10.631
(quiet knocking)

01:01:13.911 --> 01:01:15.570
Do you hear that?

01:01:16.881 --> 01:01:18.078
What?

01:01:18.113 --> 01:01:19.948
(quiet knocking
continues faster)

01:01:25.483 --> 01:01:27.252
(knocking grows louder)

01:01:27.287 --> 01:01:28.891
Oh, my God.

01:01:30.389 --> 01:01:31.718
(frantic knocking)

01:01:31.753 --> 01:01:33.291
TOBY:
Help!

01:01:34.261 --> 01:01:36.030
(ragged breathing)

01:01:36.065 --> 01:01:37.735
Help!

01:01:49.078 --> 01:01:51.111
♪ ♪

01:02:22.606 --> 01:02:24.474
CLEMENS:
Toby! Toby!

01:02:24.509 --> 01:02:27.543
(panting)

01:02:28.953 --> 01:02:30.447
Olgaren?

01:02:33.991 --> 01:02:35.320
Olgaren?

01:02:49.908 --> 01:02:52.139
-(growls)
-(yells)

01:02:53.802 --> 01:02:55.175
CLEMENS:
Help! (grunting)

01:02:55.210 --> 01:02:57.243
(yelling)

01:03:02.646 --> 01:03:04.415
Toby.

01:03:07.255 --> 01:03:08.859
Toby?

01:03:08.894 --> 01:03:11.059
-DRACULA (whispers): Toby.
-ELIOT: Open the door!

01:03:13.426 --> 01:03:16.097
-(breath hissing)
-(pounding on door)

01:03:20.400 --> 01:03:21.828
Toby, open the door.

01:03:21.863 --> 01:03:23.830
(breath hissing)

01:03:23.865 --> 01:03:25.909
♪ ♪

01:03:34.546 --> 01:03:36.315
-ELIOT: Toby?
-(pounding on door)

01:03:36.350 --> 01:03:37.844
Open the door!

01:03:37.879 --> 01:03:38.922
-(breath hissing)
-(gasps)

01:03:42.455 --> 01:03:44.158
-Open the door.
-(Olgaren yelling)

01:03:44.193 --> 01:03:45.258
Toby?

01:03:45.293 --> 01:03:47.854
Open the-- Toby! Toby!

01:03:47.889 --> 01:03:49.427
Toby!

01:03:52.696 --> 01:03:54.267
(yelling)

01:03:54.302 --> 01:03:55.499
-CLEMENS: Toby!
-ELIOT: Toby!

01:03:55.534 --> 01:03:56.907
CLEMENS:
I can't reach the lock.

01:03:56.942 --> 01:03:58.601
(grunts) Toby!

01:04:02.442 --> 01:04:04.805
♪ ♪

01:04:06.380 --> 01:04:08.809
-(growls)
-Toby!

01:04:10.615 --> 01:04:12.120
-Toby!
-Toby!

01:04:12.155 --> 01:04:14.551
(Dracula growling)

01:04:22.297 --> 01:04:24.297
(screaming)

01:04:26.664 --> 01:04:29.071
Toby! Toby!

01:04:29.106 --> 01:04:31.139
(gasping, whimpering)

01:04:33.770 --> 01:04:35.803
♪ ♪

01:04:41.019 --> 01:04:43.052
-ELIOT: Toby! Toby!
-(pounding continues)

01:04:43.087 --> 01:04:44.119
Move!

01:04:47.256 --> 01:04:49.850
-Toby!
-ELIOT: Toby!

01:04:54.329 --> 01:04:55.361
Toby!

01:04:57.530 --> 01:04:58.826
Toby!

01:05:03.338 --> 01:05:04.942
(Anna gasps)

01:05:05.934 --> 01:05:07.736
ELIOT:
Toby?

01:05:07.771 --> 01:05:10.574
Toby. Toby.

01:05:10.609 --> 01:05:12.081
Oh, my God.

01:05:12.116 --> 01:05:14.017
(breathing heavily)

01:05:24.029 --> 01:05:26.524
(yells)

01:05:29.166 --> 01:05:31.199
♪ ♪

01:05:46.348 --> 01:05:48.546
ELIOT:
You will be fine, my boy.

01:05:51.518 --> 01:05:53.980
Everything will be fine.

01:05:54.015 --> 01:05:56.719
Mr. Clemens
will take care of us.

01:06:04.025 --> 01:06:05.464
ELIOT:
<i> August 1st.</i>

01:06:05.499 --> 01:06:08.731
<i> We must be past</i>
<i> the Strait of Dover.</i>

01:06:08.766 --> 01:06:11.734
<i> Still five days to London.</i>

01:06:11.769 --> 01:06:15.969
<i> God seems to have deserted us,</i>

01:06:16.004 --> 01:06:19.907
<i> and we are drifting</i>
<i> to some terrible doom.</i>

01:06:21.779 --> 01:06:23.680
<i> Lord help us.</i>

01:06:26.553 --> 01:06:28.586
He's mad.

01:06:28.621 --> 01:06:30.192
As if possessed.

01:06:30.227 --> 01:06:32.194
-JOSEPH: Possessed by
that beast? -Oh, no, no.

01:06:32.229 --> 01:06:34.493
Not in the way you mean,
at least.

01:06:34.528 --> 01:06:37.430
It's like a poison or...

01:06:37.465 --> 01:06:38.827
an infection.

01:06:38.862 --> 01:06:41.368
WOJCHEK:
Infection?

01:06:41.403 --> 01:06:43.964
Not like any I've ever seen.

01:06:45.737 --> 01:06:47.242
(groans)

01:06:47.277 --> 01:06:49.871
I can feel it.

01:06:49.906 --> 01:06:51.543
Olgaren?

01:06:51.578 --> 01:06:52.940
Can you hear me?

01:06:53.943 --> 01:06:57.054
I can hear everything.

01:06:59.619 --> 01:07:02.389
The sea.

01:07:02.424 --> 01:07:04.457
The wind.

01:07:04.492 --> 01:07:06.789
The blood pumping in your veins.

01:07:12.269 --> 01:07:13.928
It burns.

01:07:15.932 --> 01:07:19.175
Burn?
Maybe he needs some water.

01:07:21.003 --> 01:07:23.443
(groans) It burns.

01:07:24.446 --> 01:07:26.248
-(pained grunting)
-CLEMENS: Olgaren?

01:07:26.283 --> 01:07:27.480
OLGAREN:
Burns.

01:07:30.287 --> 01:07:32.254
(groans)

01:07:32.289 --> 01:07:35.389
It burns! It burns!

01:07:35.424 --> 01:07:37.391
(quiet sizzling)

01:07:37.426 --> 01:07:39.624
It burns! (yells)

01:07:39.659 --> 01:07:41.626
It burns!

01:07:41.661 --> 01:07:43.397
(pained grunt)

01:07:43.432 --> 01:07:45.432
(screaming)

01:07:56.841 --> 01:07:58.005
(whimpers)

01:07:59.349 --> 01:08:01.382
(screaming continues)

01:08:06.653 --> 01:08:08.290
(screaming stops)

01:08:10.558 --> 01:08:12.624
♪ ♪

01:08:23.967 --> 01:08:26.143
♪ ♪

01:08:33.548 --> 01:08:35.141
(sniffles)

01:08:35.176 --> 01:08:36.879
Oh, for God's sake.

01:08:36.914 --> 01:08:39.717
Will someone say something?

01:08:42.524 --> 01:08:45.327
What the hell happened to him?

01:08:45.362 --> 01:08:47.659
I warned you.

01:08:47.694 --> 01:08:51.157
I warned all you, didn't I?

01:08:51.192 --> 01:08:54.061
It is a punishment
brought down for our sins.

01:08:54.096 --> 01:08:55.469
Petrofsky, a criminal.

01:08:55.504 --> 01:08:57.966
Olgaren, gypsy heathen.

01:08:58.001 --> 01:08:59.132
A whoremonger, a lecher.

01:08:59.167 --> 01:09:00.969
And from Gomorrah herself...

01:09:01.004 --> 01:09:04.379
Oh, will you shut the hell up,
you bleedin' idiot!

01:09:08.616 --> 01:09:13.256
Abrams, take the morning watch.

01:09:13.291 --> 01:09:15.225
And, Joseph, you are
to relieve him when he's...

01:09:15.260 --> 01:09:18.261
That child will be the next
to rise up from death.

01:09:18.296 --> 01:09:22.056
Satan's black blood pumping
corruption through his veins.

01:09:22.091 --> 01:09:25.026
God's anger has come upon
this vessel like Jonah...

01:09:25.061 --> 01:09:26.665
Just shut it up!

01:09:26.700 --> 01:09:29.569
See to the supplies.

01:09:34.708 --> 01:09:36.642
Whatever was in Olgaren...

01:09:39.075 --> 01:09:41.284
...it's fair to assume
it is in the boy.

01:09:41.319 --> 01:09:43.044
He has all the same symptoms.

01:09:43.079 --> 01:09:45.585
But your blood transfusions
saved the girl.

01:09:45.620 --> 01:09:47.455
-Not Toby.
-(sniffs)

01:09:47.490 --> 01:09:50.392
He's smaller. He's weaker.

01:09:50.427 --> 01:09:53.923
The wound was worse,
and the blood loss is greater.

01:09:53.958 --> 01:09:55.958
Just...

01:09:55.993 --> 01:09:58.268
I don't know. I think, uh...

01:10:02.967 --> 01:10:06.067
I think we might
have to start discussing...

01:10:13.417 --> 01:10:14.647
WOJCHEK:
Go on.

01:10:16.244 --> 01:10:19.619
Look him in the eye
when you do it.

01:10:19.654 --> 01:10:22.886
That's not what I meant.
That is not what I meant.

01:10:22.921 --> 01:10:25.152
It has to be hiding here.
If we can find it,

01:10:25.187 --> 01:10:27.429
I think we might be able to
figure out a way to save him...

01:10:27.464 --> 01:10:30.157
Are you sure the boy is
the one that's on your mind?

01:10:30.192 --> 01:10:32.093
Get to your bunk.

01:10:32.128 --> 01:10:35.063
We're running out of men
for the watch at this rate.

01:10:35.098 --> 01:10:37.131
♪ ♪

01:10:55.954 --> 01:10:57.393
(gasps)

01:11:00.398 --> 01:11:01.859
Anna.

01:11:09.198 --> 01:11:11.099
You're going to open
the crates, aren't you?

01:11:11.134 --> 01:11:12.507
Yes.

01:11:12.542 --> 01:11:14.971
Go back to the shed
and bolt the door.

01:11:15.006 --> 01:11:17.446
We are all trapped
on the same ship, Mr. Clemens.

01:11:17.481 --> 01:11:20.614
Are you forgetting it needs
to feed because you saved me?

01:11:20.649 --> 01:11:22.550
I'm coming with you.

01:11:22.585 --> 01:11:25.982
This thing has killed
most the crew.

01:11:26.017 --> 01:11:29.084
Then imagine what it will do
if we let it get to London.

01:11:31.726 --> 01:11:33.253
Let's go.

01:11:37.193 --> 01:11:41.536
If we do find your devil,
will bullets kill it?

01:11:43.672 --> 01:11:46.706
He has controlled my village
for generations.

01:11:46.741 --> 01:11:49.577
Do you think I have
any notion how to kill him?

01:11:49.612 --> 01:11:51.579
(Clemens grunts,
inhales sharply)

01:11:51.614 --> 01:11:52.745
(scoffs)

01:11:52.780 --> 01:11:54.582
I never liked guns.

01:11:54.617 --> 01:11:56.617
I want you to have...

01:12:07.124 --> 01:12:09.399
Let's see. Sixth of July.

01:12:09.434 --> 01:12:12.358
Private cargo consigned
for Carfax Abbey in London.

01:12:12.393 --> 01:12:15.064
Doesn't say the owner.

01:12:17.035 --> 01:12:19.739
♪ ♪

01:12:21.237 --> 01:12:22.940
(inhales sharply)

01:12:37.792 --> 01:12:39.055
(sharp thump)

01:12:39.992 --> 01:12:42.432
He told Jonah,
and he was spared.

01:12:43.996 --> 01:12:45.897
He was spared.

01:12:45.932 --> 01:12:49.868
"I cried out to the Lord
because of my affliction,

01:12:49.903 --> 01:12:51.199
"and he answered me.

01:12:51.234 --> 01:12:53.476
"Out of the belly of Sheol
I cried,

01:12:53.511 --> 01:12:55.874
"and you heard my voice.

01:12:55.909 --> 01:12:57.480
-(boat creaking)
-(grunting)

01:12:58.945 --> 01:13:03.717
"For you cast me into the deep,

01:13:03.752 --> 01:13:06.687
into the heart of the seas."

01:13:08.350 --> 01:13:10.493
(Clemens grunts)

01:13:10.528 --> 01:13:12.825
-CLEMENS: Why London?
-ANNA: Because in my country,

01:13:12.860 --> 01:13:14.288
there is no one left
to feed on.

01:13:14.323 --> 01:13:16.356
♪ ♪

01:13:29.712 --> 01:13:31.778
(low growling)

01:13:40.382 --> 01:13:42.459
Let's start with this one.

01:13:45.893 --> 01:13:47.354
(grunts)

01:13:50.799 --> 01:13:51.996
(grunts)

01:13:53.131 --> 01:13:54.394
(grunts)

01:14:00.369 --> 01:14:01.709
(grunts)

01:14:01.744 --> 01:14:03.304
(panting)

01:14:04.505 --> 01:14:05.977
(grunts)

01:14:09.917 --> 01:14:11.983
(panting)

01:14:12.986 --> 01:14:14.150
Dirt.

01:14:14.185 --> 01:14:16.449
It's nothing but dirt.

01:14:16.484 --> 01:14:17.725
(sighs)

01:14:20.356 --> 01:14:21.795
(grunts)

01:14:21.830 --> 01:14:24.226
-(Clemens grunting)
-(crowbar clanking)

01:14:31.741 --> 01:14:34.071
(chuckles) Nothing.

01:14:35.041 --> 01:14:37.778
♪ ♪

01:14:43.951 --> 01:14:46.017
ANNA:
This one looks different.

01:14:50.793 --> 01:14:52.452
♪ ♪

01:14:55.292 --> 01:14:57.127
(Clemens grunts)

01:15:05.467 --> 01:15:08.776
(both grunting)

01:15:10.472 --> 01:15:11.911
ANNA:
Look.

01:15:25.454 --> 01:15:26.552
(grunts)

01:15:26.587 --> 01:15:28.455
(ship creaking)

01:15:28.490 --> 01:15:30.567
♪ ♪

01:15:48.015 --> 01:15:49.916
(grunts)

01:15:51.414 --> 01:15:52.919
♪ ♪

01:16:07.364 --> 01:16:09.364
We have found
where the devil sleeps.

01:16:15.009 --> 01:16:17.273
(panting)

01:16:17.308 --> 01:16:20.111
(grunting)

01:16:24.282 --> 01:16:26.579
(wind whistles softly)

01:16:26.614 --> 01:16:29.219
-(heavy flapping)
-(Joseph gasping softly)

01:16:34.127 --> 01:16:36.160
-(low growling)
-(heavy flapping)

01:16:37.801 --> 01:16:39.130
(gasps)

01:16:39.165 --> 01:16:42.265
-(panting)
-(breath hissing)

01:16:42.300 --> 01:16:45.433
DRACULA (whispering):
"I cried,

01:16:45.468 --> 01:16:52.209
and you heard my voice."

01:16:53.509 --> 01:16:55.179
(crying softly)

01:16:55.214 --> 01:16:56.477
Oh, Lord...

01:16:56.512 --> 01:16:58.050
DRACULA:
Oh, Lord.

01:16:58.085 --> 01:16:59.282
Oh, God. (crying softly)

01:16:59.317 --> 01:17:02.351
DRACULA:
Oh, God.

01:17:04.190 --> 01:17:06.223
♪ ♪

01:17:11.362 --> 01:17:13.296
(growling)

01:17:13.331 --> 01:17:14.495
Oh, God!

01:17:14.530 --> 01:17:17.333
(bell clanging in distance)

01:17:17.368 --> 01:17:20.138
ABRAMS: Hey!
The starboard lifeboat's gone!

01:17:20.173 --> 01:17:22.173
WOJCHEK:
Abrams, do you see it?

01:17:22.208 --> 01:17:25.044
No. There's nothing here.

01:17:25.079 --> 01:17:26.540
Nothing.

01:17:32.284 --> 01:17:34.548
(Wojchek gasps)

01:17:34.583 --> 01:17:36.220
(softly):
No.

01:17:43.097 --> 01:17:44.525
(door thumps)

01:17:44.560 --> 01:17:47.198
Sir, not supposing you heard?

01:17:52.271 --> 01:17:53.776
(sighs)

01:17:55.241 --> 01:17:58.077
You would have made
a good captain, Mr. Wojchek.

01:17:59.916 --> 01:18:03.412
(sighs)
If we had just seen London.

01:18:15.261 --> 01:18:17.129
(footsteps approaching)

01:18:17.164 --> 01:18:18.724
Mr. Wojchek.

01:18:18.759 --> 01:18:21.463
How's Toby?
Shall I bring him some...

01:18:28.109 --> 01:18:31.374
What the hell is happening
on this ship?!

01:18:31.409 --> 01:18:33.442
♪ ♪

01:18:45.291 --> 01:18:47.896
CLEMENS:
Captain Eliot.

01:18:47.931 --> 01:18:50.096
We've, uh...

01:18:50.131 --> 01:18:53.132
we've wrapped Toby's body
in canvas, sir.

01:18:56.764 --> 01:18:59.270
We're a doomed crew,
Mr. Clemens.

01:19:01.538 --> 01:19:04.110
On a doomed ship.

01:19:04.145 --> 01:19:06.816
We no longer plot our course.

01:19:06.851 --> 01:19:09.918
The devil below does.

01:19:09.953 --> 01:19:12.646
And we all know
where he plans to deliver us.

01:19:15.651 --> 01:19:17.684
To hell, Mr. Clemens.

01:19:18.995 --> 01:19:23.294
Each of us, one by one.

01:19:30.875 --> 01:19:32.633
(Wojchek sniffles)

01:19:33.669 --> 01:19:34.943
Captain?

01:19:34.978 --> 01:19:37.011
♪ ♪

01:19:46.847 --> 01:19:48.748
Dear Lord...

01:19:51.995 --> 01:19:53.654
...take this sweet boy.

01:19:55.097 --> 01:19:57.559
May he never again be hungry,

01:19:57.594 --> 01:19:59.528
never be cold...

01:20:01.004 --> 01:20:02.564
...never be scared.

01:20:04.832 --> 01:20:07.173
This world is
cruel and uncaring.

01:20:09.441 --> 01:20:12.376
May Toby find his next home
to be a kinder one.

01:20:14.017 --> 01:20:15.346
Amen.

01:20:16.349 --> 01:20:17.381
Amen.

01:20:18.384 --> 01:20:19.889
Amen.

01:20:22.883 --> 01:20:24.058
Wait.

01:20:27.195 --> 01:20:29.789
I saw him move. He's alive.

01:20:31.859 --> 01:20:36.499
CLEMENS: Captain Eliot, the boy
has no breath in his body.

01:20:36.534 --> 01:20:39.403
He has no heartbeat. He's gone.

01:20:39.438 --> 01:20:41.669
Uh...

01:20:41.704 --> 01:20:44.276
Captain, you should sit.

01:20:44.311 --> 01:20:48.082
I tell you, he's alive.
He moved.

01:20:48.117 --> 01:20:50.051
CLEMENS:
Captain Eliot, please.

01:21:03.132 --> 01:21:05.594
(Toby and Eliot screaming)

01:21:07.103 --> 01:21:08.905
(shouting)

01:21:10.172 --> 01:21:12.898
(screaming continues)

01:21:12.933 --> 01:21:14.603
-(shouts)
-No!

01:21:14.638 --> 01:21:16.671
♪ ♪

01:21:22.250 --> 01:21:24.679
♪ ♪

01:21:48.771 --> 01:21:50.804
♪ ♪

01:22:10.562 --> 01:22:12.232
(Eliot sighs)

01:22:14.170 --> 01:22:17.699
CLEMENS (quietly): Mr. Wojchek,
can I... can I speak with you?

01:22:20.000 --> 01:22:22.209
We have a plan. If we can...

01:22:22.244 --> 01:22:24.970
You seen what I seen
and you still want to plan.

01:22:25.005 --> 01:22:27.313
This ain't Cambridge,
astronomer.

01:22:27.348 --> 01:22:29.843
You can't think your way
out of this one.

01:22:31.715 --> 01:22:33.451
I was one of
the first Black doctors

01:22:33.486 --> 01:22:35.057
to graduate from Cambridge
with medical degree.

01:22:35.092 --> 01:22:36.355
Have I told you that?

01:22:36.390 --> 01:22:37.884
Well, that's very nice
for you...

01:22:37.919 --> 01:22:39.721
I applied to all the best
hospitals in the country.

01:22:39.756 --> 01:22:42.361
Immediately, I was told there
were no positions available.

01:22:42.396 --> 01:22:46.134
I fought tooth and nail
for my education,

01:22:46.169 --> 01:22:48.829
and yet no one
would let me practice it.

01:22:48.864 --> 01:22:51.667
Finally, I was offered
a position by post.

01:22:51.702 --> 01:22:55.671
Royal physician to King Carol
the First of Romania.

01:22:55.706 --> 01:22:58.377
My name,
it reached them somehow.

01:22:59.710 --> 01:23:02.216
But the color of my skin,
it would later seem, had not.

01:23:10.622 --> 01:23:14.492
Captain Eliot once asked me
over dinner

01:23:14.527 --> 01:23:16.692
what I most desired.

01:23:16.727 --> 01:23:19.596
I told him I wanted
the world to make sense.

01:23:22.062 --> 01:23:26.900
I need this world
to make sense, Mr. Wojchek.

01:23:28.871 --> 01:23:31.278
This beast--

01:23:31.313 --> 01:23:35.546
and mark my words,
it is a beast--

01:23:35.581 --> 01:23:37.449
deep down,
I need it to make sense, too.

01:23:37.484 --> 01:23:39.121
I need to know why

01:23:39.156 --> 01:23:41.255
it is the way it is
and why it does what it does.

01:23:41.290 --> 01:23:42.883
And then I will remind
the beast that it,

01:23:42.918 --> 01:23:45.919
like the world,
has absolutely no hold over me.

01:23:45.954 --> 01:23:47.756
And then?

01:23:48.759 --> 01:23:51.067
And then I want to kill
the cursed thing.

01:23:54.171 --> 01:23:56.732
If we barricade this cabin,

01:23:56.767 --> 01:23:59.867
we are a day from London
with this wind.

01:23:59.902 --> 01:24:02.903
Can't set more sail,
crew what it is.

01:24:02.938 --> 01:24:04.872
CLEMENS: What, you want us to
wait around, eyes in the dark,

01:24:04.907 --> 01:24:06.412
served up and ready for dinner?

01:24:06.447 --> 01:24:08.381
WOJCHEK: It ran
from our guns in the night.

01:24:08.416 --> 01:24:09.481
It won't risk
an outright attack.

01:24:09.516 --> 01:24:11.417
-ANNA: Running?
-It's...

01:24:11.452 --> 01:24:13.617
It was not running.

01:24:13.652 --> 01:24:15.047
(gun clicking)

01:24:15.082 --> 01:24:16.323
It was rationing.

01:24:17.656 --> 01:24:19.491
Rationing?

01:24:21.693 --> 01:24:23.759
(gun racks)

01:24:26.126 --> 01:24:28.335
One a night.

01:24:28.370 --> 01:24:31.800
Once we had hit open waters
and could no longer make port.

01:24:35.036 --> 01:24:37.608
It hid below deck,

01:24:37.643 --> 01:24:41.007
sustaining off Anna until then.

01:24:44.188 --> 01:24:46.518
But now it has us right where
it wants us, doesn't it?

01:24:46.553 --> 01:24:49.015
Like he said,
London's only a day away.

01:24:50.623 --> 01:24:52.821
It no longer needs us.

01:24:52.856 --> 01:24:56.660
So we have to kill it
before it reaches the coast.

01:24:56.695 --> 01:24:58.365
ABRAMS:
Kill it?

01:24:58.400 --> 01:25:00.928
We can't even find it.

01:25:00.963 --> 01:25:03.304
No, we can't.

01:25:03.339 --> 01:25:05.537
It is why we're to set a trap.

01:25:05.572 --> 01:25:07.506
We must sink the ship.

01:25:07.541 --> 01:25:09.475
With him on it.

01:25:09.510 --> 01:25:10.872
Scuttle the<i> Demeter?</i>

01:25:10.907 --> 01:25:12.808
Have you gone mad?!

01:25:12.843 --> 01:25:14.645
CLEMENS:
She's right.

01:25:14.680 --> 01:25:16.647
We set up an ambush and
leave it on the sinking ship.

01:25:16.682 --> 01:25:19.320
Then we can escape
on one of the lifeboats.

01:25:19.355 --> 01:25:21.949
If the course is right, we
should be able to make shore.

01:25:21.984 --> 01:25:23.621
This is my home.

01:25:23.656 --> 01:25:28.054
And I won't tear her apart
for this fucking thing!

01:25:28.089 --> 01:25:29.528
I grew up on a boat,
Mr. Wojchek.

01:25:29.563 --> 01:25:31.530
Just like this one.

01:25:31.565 --> 01:25:34.203
My father was a deckhand
his whole life.

01:25:34.238 --> 01:25:36.469
He always told me that the...

01:25:36.504 --> 01:25:40.407
the ship, the living part,

01:25:40.442 --> 01:25:41.672
is the men on board.

01:25:41.707 --> 01:25:43.069
The crews.

01:25:43.104 --> 01:25:45.379
The stories.

01:25:45.414 --> 01:25:47.909
Everything else is
just timber and nails.

01:25:48.846 --> 01:25:50.285
No!

01:25:53.048 --> 01:25:54.388
This is my home.

01:25:57.052 --> 01:25:58.227
She's mine.

01:26:05.533 --> 01:26:07.797
It's going to be me.

01:26:08.800 --> 01:26:11.097
CLEMENS:
<i> We barricade the hold,</i>

01:26:11.132 --> 01:26:14.100
<i> so that he only has</i>
<i> one way out on deck.</i>

01:26:14.135 --> 01:26:17.840
<i> As night falls,</i>
<i> Anna will be at the helm.</i>

01:26:17.875 --> 01:26:19.941
<i> When it comes for her,</i>

01:26:19.976 --> 01:26:23.175
<i> we'll have a clear shot</i>
<i> from the crow's nest.</i>

01:26:23.210 --> 01:26:24.880
<i> We sink the ship</i>

01:26:24.915 --> 01:26:27.421
<i> and send the wounded beast</i>
<i> to a watery grave.</i>

01:26:32.560 --> 01:26:36.056
<i> (hissing breath echoing)</i>

01:26:39.259 --> 01:26:41.303
(ship creaking)

01:26:43.802 --> 01:26:46.275
(door creaks)

01:26:53.108 --> 01:26:54.778
ELIOT:
21 July.

01:26:54.813 --> 01:26:56.285
Fourth August.

01:26:56.320 --> 01:26:58.650
It dare not touch--
You got to get Toby home.

01:26:58.685 --> 01:26:59.750
1830...

01:26:59.785 --> 01:27:00.982
Captain.

01:27:01.017 --> 01:27:03.083
No, uh, people need to know.

01:27:03.118 --> 01:27:05.459
Uh, logs.
There needs to be a record.

01:27:05.494 --> 01:27:06.988
The<i> Demeter</i> is lost, sir.

01:27:07.023 --> 01:27:08.660
We're abandoning ship.

01:27:10.664 --> 01:27:11.828
Abandoning ship?

01:27:11.863 --> 01:27:13.962
Aye, sir.

01:27:17.935 --> 01:27:21.706
Mr. Wojchek's below deck making
preparations as we speak.

01:27:23.006 --> 01:27:24.478
We'll leave the beast
a sinking ship

01:27:24.513 --> 01:27:26.810
as a farewell gift. (gasps)

01:27:31.014 --> 01:27:32.453
He comes to me.

01:27:34.523 --> 01:27:37.623
He whispers to me
behind my own eyes.

01:27:40.892 --> 01:27:43.189
He can bring Toby back.

01:27:43.224 --> 01:27:44.993
He took him away.
He can bring him back.

01:27:45.028 --> 01:27:46.698
Captain, come to your senses.

01:27:46.733 --> 01:27:48.161
You know that's not possible.

01:27:48.196 --> 01:27:50.768
Toby... (breathing heavily)

01:27:50.803 --> 01:27:52.440
Toby.

01:27:52.475 --> 01:27:55.377
I just need to bring
the<i> Demeter</i> to shore.

01:27:55.412 --> 01:27:57.445
I'm sorry, Mr. Clemens.

01:27:57.480 --> 01:27:59.645
-No! -ANNA: Captain.
-(breath shudders)

01:27:59.680 --> 01:28:00.976
You have seen him as I have.

01:28:01.011 --> 01:28:02.549
You know deep down
that is not all.

01:28:09.987 --> 01:28:13.021
(breath shuddering)

01:28:15.223 --> 01:28:18.367
When I dream, sometimes...

01:28:18.402 --> 01:28:19.962
I remember who I was.

01:28:19.997 --> 01:28:22.228
Before him.

01:28:22.263 --> 01:28:26.936
But most often, I think of
the box he kept me in.

01:28:28.544 --> 01:28:32.909
How every time he came for me
and tore into my flesh,

01:28:32.944 --> 01:28:35.846
drank his fill,

01:28:35.881 --> 01:28:38.915
dirt would seep into
the fresh wound,

01:28:38.950 --> 01:28:40.180
filling me up.

01:28:41.216 --> 01:28:43.216
You cannot sink the<i> Demeter.</i>

01:28:43.251 --> 01:28:45.020
Picture Toby's face.

01:28:46.023 --> 01:28:49.057
His smile, his laugh.

01:28:50.291 --> 01:28:52.258
And think of that dirt
filling him up, too,

01:28:52.293 --> 01:28:55.569
because that's
what the devil does.

01:28:55.604 --> 01:28:59.738
He takes what is good
and what you love, and he...

01:28:59.773 --> 01:29:03.808
he uses it, and he twists it,
and he rots it from within.

01:29:05.944 --> 01:29:08.516
Do not let him do that
to the memory of your boy.

01:29:08.551 --> 01:29:10.518
(breath shuddering)

01:29:10.553 --> 01:29:12.586
♪ ♪

01:29:38.944 --> 01:29:41.483
♪ ♪

01:29:47.150 --> 01:29:48.952
I will...

01:29:50.087 --> 01:29:53.352
I will sail the ship
out to sea.

01:29:56.258 --> 01:29:58.291
And when she finally goes...

01:30:01.263 --> 01:30:05.705
...the monster will never be
able to reach the home I knew.

01:30:07.643 --> 01:30:08.840
That Toby knew.

01:30:08.875 --> 01:30:10.644
Captain,

01:30:10.679 --> 01:30:13.174
there's no need for you
to stay on board the<i> Demeter.</i>

01:30:17.378 --> 01:30:19.785
Where would I go, Mr. Clemens?

01:30:23.989 --> 01:30:26.022
♪ ♪

01:30:35.869 --> 01:30:37.902
(ship creaking)

01:30:42.502 --> 01:30:44.469
ABRAMS:
Do you think this'll work?

01:30:44.504 --> 01:30:46.207
It has to.

01:30:49.014 --> 01:30:51.146
-ABRAMS: There she is.
-(thunder rumbling)

01:30:51.181 --> 01:30:53.313
The shores of England.

01:30:53.348 --> 01:30:55.656
And looks like
there's a storm blowing in.

01:30:55.691 --> 01:30:57.724
Keep your eyes on the deck.

01:30:57.759 --> 01:30:59.495
(breath hisses softly)

01:31:02.489 --> 01:31:04.533
♪ ♪

01:31:28.691 --> 01:31:30.724
♪ ♪

01:31:54.244 --> 01:31:56.618
I can't see a bloody thing.

01:31:59.447 --> 01:32:00.721
Quiet.

01:32:06.322 --> 01:32:07.959
You don't need to be here.

01:32:08.962 --> 01:32:11.897
You could stay below deck
with Captain Eliot.

01:32:13.461 --> 01:32:15.164
Stay safe.

01:32:16.673 --> 01:32:19.564
We are connected,
the devil and I.

01:32:19.599 --> 01:32:22.743
You are smart enough
to have noticed.

01:32:22.778 --> 01:32:24.976
I can sense him.

01:32:26.276 --> 01:32:28.276
Feel him somehow.

01:32:30.016 --> 01:32:31.851
He feels it, too.

01:32:34.020 --> 01:32:35.921
He will come for me.

01:32:37.485 --> 01:32:40.057
And while he's focused on me,
you know what to do.

01:32:40.092 --> 01:32:42.488
♪ ♪

01:32:55.976 --> 01:32:58.009
(low growling)

01:33:08.516 --> 01:33:11.517
(breath hissing)

01:33:13.653 --> 01:33:15.895
ABRAMS:
Where the bloody hell is it?

01:33:25.841 --> 01:33:27.335
